name: thousand layer fries
source: https://youtu.be/bpg1DwnbSwI
notes: |
  Fallow's take on Tom Booton's (The Dorchester) pommes Pont-Neuf / mille-feuille potato.
  Two things people get wrong: not cooking the potato long enough (leftover moisture expands
  when fried and the layers fall apart) and not pressing long enough after cooking.
  Serves ~6. Scale up or down freely. Don't freeze — remaining moisture stops it holding together.
components:
  - name: terrine
    ingredients:
      - item: agria potatoes
        note: starchy; peel but DO NOT wash — keep the starch, it binds the layers
      - item: beef fat
        note: 50/50 with clarified butter; either is optional
      - item: clarified butter
        note: 50/50 with beef fat
      - item: corn flour
        note: light dusting between layers for extra bind; too much goes gummy
      - salt
    steps:
      - peel potatoes (do not wash) and slice lengthwise on a mandolin, very thin (almost see-through)
      - line a mould with greaseproof paper
      - layer the slices all the same direction, for structural integrity
      - lightly salt and lightly dust corn flour layer by layer through a sieve
      - prick all over
      - warm the fat to ~110°C and pour over so it soaks into the middle, not just the sides
      - cover the top with parchment
      - bake at 140°C for ~3 hours (too hot caramelises the top before the inside cooks; too cold takes 5-6 hrs)
      - check done — a knife through the paper meets no resistance
      - press with a weight (couple of pints of milk / big bottle of oil) and chill in the fridge 5-6 hours
      - portion into chunky chip shapes
      - fry in neutral oil at 180°C for ~5 mins, moving so they don't stick to the bottom
      - season with fine salt straight out of the fryer (mix is already salted, go light)
  - name: cheese & bacon sauce
    ingredients:
      - item: whole egg
        mass: 75
        note: ~2 eggs
      - item: egg yolk
        mass: 120
        note: ~6 yolks
      - water
      - cream
      - item: paprika
        note: mostly for colour
      - item: red Leicester
        note: finely grated (or red cheddar)
      - item: American cheese
      - salt
      - item: Dijon mustard
        note: a little, for acidity
      - item: bacon
        note: cut into lardons
    steps:
      - whisk eggs, yolks, water, cream and paprika together
      - cook over a bain-marie (water lightly simmering), whisking constantly, up to 75°C until custard-like
      - grate in red Leicester finely, then add American cheese and turn the heat off; keep warm to melt in
      - stir (switch off the whisk — don't incorporate air) until glossy
      - season with salt and stir in Dijon
      - fry bacon lardons and scatter over the top to serve
